```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        String[] lines = scanner.nextLine().split(", ");

        double sum = 0;
        double kilobytes = 0;
        double megabytes = 0;
        double gigabytes = 0;

        for (String line : lines) {
            String[] parts = line.split(" ");

            double number = Double.parseDouble(parts[0]);
            String suffix = parts[1];

            if (suffix.equals("k") || suffix.equals("K")) {
                number *= 1024;
            } else if (suffix.equals("m") || suffix.equals("M")) {
                number *= 1024 * 1024;
            } else if (suffix.equals("g") || suffix.equals("G")) {
                number *= 1024 * 1024 * 1024;
            }

            sum += number;
            kilobytes += number;
            megabytes += number;
            gigabytes += number;

            System.out.printf("%.1f %f k %f M %f G\n", sum, kilobytes, megabytes, gigabytes);
        }

        scanner.close();
    }
}
```

This program first reads the input from the standard input and splits it into lines. Then, for each line, it splits it into a number and a suffix. It converts the number to its corresponding base value based on the suffix and adds it to the total sum. It also calculates the sum in kilobytes, megabytes, and gigabytes and prints the results with one decimal place. Finally, it closes the `Scanner` object after it's no longer needed. [end of text]


